00:00:31.017 --> 00:00:32.350
DEAN BUONOMANO: Thank you, Carl.

00:00:32.350 --> 00:00:33.980
And thank you all
for coming today.

00:00:33.980 --> 00:00:35.390
It's a pleasure to be here.

00:00:35.390 --> 00:00:38.170
So I'd like to talk
a bit about time

00:00:38.170 --> 00:00:41.440
and the brain and the brain
in the nature of time.

00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:43.570
And to get my talk
started, I'd like

00:00:43.570 --> 00:00:51.070
to start by creating
a awkward silence.

00:00:51.070 --> 00:00:53.070
And I'd like to do that
to make three points.

00:00:53.070 --> 00:00:55.700
The first is that your
brain is automatically

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:57.860
attempting to predict
what is about to happen.

00:00:57.860 --> 00:00:59.602
Your brain is a
prediction machine.

00:00:59.602 --> 00:01:01.310
So right there you
were trying to predict

00:01:01.310 --> 00:01:02.351
what was about to happen.

00:01:02.351 --> 00:01:05.870
Maybe you were thinking, uh-oh,
he's having an absent seizure.

00:01:05.870 --> 00:01:09.140
Number two, your brain is
automatically telling time.

00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:11.690
The only reason you
could notice that pause

00:01:11.690 --> 00:01:14.990
is because you're creating
a temporal expectation

00:01:14.990 --> 00:01:18.650
of the normal average
pause between words.

00:01:18.650 --> 00:01:21.500
And that temporal
pause was violated

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:25.430
and that's when the passage of
time came to your attention.

00:01:25.430 --> 00:01:26.930
And that's my
point number three.

00:01:26.930 --> 00:01:31.340
You probably became aware
of the passage of time.

00:01:31.340 --> 00:01:35.150
The subjective feeling
of time going slowly

00:01:35.150 --> 00:01:37.520
because it was a slightly
awkward moment and time

00:01:37.520 --> 00:01:40.200
probably seemed
to be going slowly

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:44.669
and, hopefully, it wasn't
as long as it seemed to be.

00:01:44.669 --> 00:01:46.460
At least I hope it
wasn't, because to me it

00:01:46.460 --> 00:01:48.610
seemed like a full minute.

00:01:48.610 --> 00:01:51.950
But before we delve in
to the mechanisms of how

00:01:51.950 --> 00:01:54.860
the brain tells time and the
meaning of the nature of time,

00:01:54.860 --> 00:01:56.720
let me already start
off by pointing out

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:01.441
that I've used the word time
a number of times in this talk

00:02:01.441 --> 00:02:01.940
already.

00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:03.860
And I assume you
know what I mean.

00:02:03.860 --> 00:02:06.250
And you assume I know
what the word means.

00:02:06.250 --> 00:02:08.240
But is that the case?

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:09.620
Can we actually define time?

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:18.800
It turns out that the word
time is the most common noun

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:22.370
in the English language,
along with two others that are

00:02:22.370 --> 00:02:25.080
units of time, year and day.

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:28.370
So this is an obvious
indication of how important

00:02:28.370 --> 00:02:30.440
time is in our lives.

00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:33.440
But it's a bit ironic
that the most common noun

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:36.550
in the English language is one
that we really can't define.

00:02:36.550 --> 00:02:39.530
It's a bit embarrassing,
actually, isn't it?

00:02:39.530 --> 00:02:43.160
So this brings us to the
problem, how do we define time?

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:47.400
And people have struggled with
this for a long, long time.

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:51.740
So 1,600 years ago,
St. Augustine said,

00:02:51.740 --> 00:02:52.569
"What then is time?

00:02:52.569 --> 00:02:54.110
If no one asks me,
I know what it is.

00:02:54.110 --> 00:02:57.110
If I wish to explain it to
him who asks, I do not know."

00:02:59.780 --> 00:03:04.820
1,600 years later, the great
physicist, Richard Feynman,

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:07.220
who's not one to give
up easily on problems,

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:09.724
basically gave up and said,
"Maybe it's just as well if we

00:03:09.724 --> 00:03:12.140
face the fact that time is one
of those things we probably

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:13.040
cannot define.

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:15.680
What matters anyways is
not how we define time,

00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:18.470
but how we measure it."

00:03:18.470 --> 00:03:21.680
But it was probably the
author Douglas Adams

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:24.630
that gave us the most
important definition of time.

00:03:24.630 --> 00:03:29.120
"Time is an illusion,
lunchtime doubly so."

00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:33.190
So part of the problem is
that the word time really

00:03:33.190 --> 00:03:34.527
means different things, right?

00:03:34.527 --> 00:03:36.610
And let me give you this
rather contrived sentence

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:37.750
to make that point.

00:03:37.750 --> 00:03:41.620
Einstein's talk on the nature
of time started on time

00:03:41.620 --> 00:03:45.050
but seemed to last a long time.

00:03:45.050 --> 00:03:48.040
OK, so first the
nature of time, so that

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:49.990
refers to the physics of time.

00:03:49.990 --> 00:03:54.590
Is time a full blown dimension,
as in the four dimensions

00:03:54.590 --> 00:03:55.090
of time?

00:03:55.090 --> 00:03:57.250
Does only the present exist?

00:03:57.250 --> 00:04:01.090
Is time a abstraction
that we scientists

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:03.550
use to help us
understand the universe?

00:04:03.550 --> 00:04:06.280
Second, started on
time, that's clock time.

00:04:06.280 --> 00:04:08.380
That's the easiest
time to define, right?

00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:11.020
That's time as defined
as what clocks tell.

00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:12.960
As circular as
that definition is,

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:15.310
it's a really useful one and
probably the most important

00:04:15.310 --> 00:04:18.880
in that it got all
of us here on time.

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:21.490
The last one is the
subjective feeling of time.

00:04:21.490 --> 00:04:23.860
So it seemed to
last a long time.

00:04:23.860 --> 00:04:28.730
And that's tightly linked to
the problem of consciousness.

00:04:28.730 --> 00:04:31.660
So in that sense, the
subjective sense of time

00:04:31.660 --> 00:04:36.340
is also a very difficult
problem to address.

00:04:36.340 --> 00:04:42.670
Now starting with
the first question,

00:04:42.670 --> 00:04:45.340
time is really important
to how the brain works.

00:04:45.340 --> 00:04:47.380
And this is why I
consider, in many ways,

00:04:47.380 --> 00:04:49.930
the brain to be, if you
will, a time machine.

00:04:49.930 --> 00:04:51.370
And there's four
reasons for that.

00:04:51.370 --> 00:04:53.740
The brain is a machine
that tells time.

00:04:53.740 --> 00:04:56.050
The brain generates
the subjective feeling

00:04:56.050 --> 00:04:57.730
of the passage of time.

00:04:57.730 --> 00:04:59.800
The brain attempts to
predict the future.

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:05.300
The brain remembers the past
in order to predict the future.

00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:10.382
And finally, the brain allows
us to mentally project ourselves

00:05:10.382 --> 00:05:12.090
into the past or the
future, something we

00:05:12.090 --> 00:05:13.620
call Mental Time Travel.

00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:18.430
And this is really
important for our ability

00:05:18.430 --> 00:05:21.970
to interact with
the world, in terms

00:05:21.970 --> 00:05:24.700
of what makes humans
unique is our ability

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:26.320
to engage in mental time travel.

00:05:26.320 --> 00:05:27.970
And we'll talk a
bit more about this.

00:05:27.970 --> 00:05:30.160
But first, consider
the first issue here,

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:31.690
the brain is a time machine.

00:05:31.690 --> 00:05:36.190
So the brain tells time
across 12 orders of magnitude,

00:05:36.190 --> 00:05:41.170
from microseconds at the lower
end over there to down here,

00:05:41.170 --> 00:05:44.020
which you're using right
now, for sound localization.

00:05:44.020 --> 00:05:47.140
So your brain picks up
the tens or hundreds

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:49.780
of micro-seconds delays
it takes sound to arrive

00:05:49.780 --> 00:05:53.020
from my left ear to my right
ear by picking up the delta t's,

00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:56.140
the relative time delays there.

00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:59.950
Time perception and
speech, on the order

00:05:59.950 --> 00:06:02.050
of hundreds of
milliseconds and seconds,

00:06:02.050 --> 00:06:05.770
music, motor coordination
is happening on this range

00:06:05.770 --> 00:06:06.820
of time perception.

00:06:06.820 --> 00:06:08.570
And we'll delve more into that.

00:06:08.570 --> 00:06:11.607
And then we have
time estimation,

00:06:11.607 --> 00:06:13.690
which is sort of what most
people think of when we

00:06:13.690 --> 00:06:15.140
talk about their sense of time.

00:06:17.890 --> 00:06:19.570
How long has this
talk been lasting?

00:06:19.570 --> 00:06:22.480
How long has the red light
been waiting to change?

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:23.197
And so forth.

00:06:23.197 --> 00:06:25.030
And finally, you have
your circadian rhythms

00:06:25.030 --> 00:06:26.738
that everybody is
familiar with, in terms

00:06:26.738 --> 00:06:29.950
of controlling your clock,
when to get up in the morning,

00:06:29.950 --> 00:06:31.870
and when to go to bed.

00:06:31.870 --> 00:06:33.890
So how does the brain tell time?

00:06:33.890 --> 00:06:38.557
So to answer that question, it's
useful to think about timing

00:06:38.557 --> 00:06:39.640
in these different scales.

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:42.670
So for example, in language,
a couple of examples

00:06:42.670 --> 00:06:47.260
here are if I say something
like, they gave her cat food

00:06:47.260 --> 00:06:49.490
or they gave her cat food.

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:52.300
So there you're using
the pause in speech

00:06:52.300 --> 00:06:56.296
to determine the
meaning of the sentence.

00:06:56.296 --> 00:06:57.670
And by the way,
this is something

00:06:57.670 --> 00:07:02.320
that artificial speech systems
still struggle with a bit.

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:04.050
This is one of the
challenges and it's

00:07:04.050 --> 00:07:06.040
the cause of some
of the mistakes

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:09.800
that are still made, even with
the most advanced systems.

00:07:09.800 --> 00:07:13.810
Now another example
here is in music.

00:07:13.810 --> 00:07:19.420
And now I'm going to play
to you a piece of music.

00:07:19.420 --> 00:07:22.540
And the task here is it's
a hybrid piece of music

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:24.580
and see if it reminds
you of anything.

00:07:24.580 --> 00:07:25.970
But the time has been altered.

00:07:25.970 --> 00:07:27.710
And I know some of you
were here at the beginning

00:07:27.710 --> 00:07:29.540
and you probably saw
the next slide here.

00:07:29.540 --> 00:07:31.160
So you're going
have to keep quiet.

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:35.186
But Google, please
play music here.

00:07:35.186 --> 00:07:37.531
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:07:40.350 --> 00:07:42.980
So does this remind you of any
piece of music you know of?

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:45.806
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:07:50.050 --> 00:07:51.520
So I'll give you a hint.

00:07:51.520 --> 00:07:53.260
You guys are a
young crowd but it's

00:07:53.260 --> 00:07:56.435
from a group called the Beatles.

00:07:56.435 --> 00:07:58.810
Does it remind anybody, does
that ring a bell to anybody?

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:00.738
Can anybody pick
up what that was?

00:08:00.738 --> 00:08:01.238
Yeah?

00:08:01.238 --> 00:08:02.720
AUDIENCE: Yellow Submarine.

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:04.170
DEAN BUONOMANO: OK, very good.

00:08:04.170 --> 00:08:05.190
Anything else?

00:08:05.190 --> 00:08:08.620
Anybody else, does it remind
you of any other song?

00:08:08.620 --> 00:08:10.730
So that's a hybrid song there.

00:08:10.730 --> 00:08:14.145
So what that was was
the notes, so you

00:08:14.145 --> 00:08:17.440
were paying more attention
to the notes, the melody,

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:20.800
of Yellow Submarine, but it
was the timing of Yesterday.

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:23.140
So we sort of did
a hybrid crossing

00:08:23.140 --> 00:08:26.630
of the spatial information
and the temporal information.

00:08:26.630 --> 00:08:28.219
So sometimes people
pick up a bit more

00:08:28.219 --> 00:08:30.010
on the temporal structure,
sometimes people

00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:31.810
pick up more on the melody.

00:08:31.810 --> 00:08:33.730
But this is just to
make the obvious point

00:08:33.730 --> 00:08:39.429
that, without time and ability
to perceive and tell time,

00:08:39.429 --> 00:08:41.020
music, of course,
wouldn't exist.

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:44.410
And indeed, it's in
this scale of tens

00:08:44.410 --> 00:08:49.490
to hundreds of milliseconds
that time is most important.

00:08:49.490 --> 00:08:53.630
So in the context of
the lab, for example,

00:08:53.630 --> 00:08:55.724
one question we ask is
whatever the mechanisms

00:08:55.724 --> 00:08:57.640
within your brain that
allow you to tell time,

00:08:57.640 --> 00:09:00.310
can they improve with practice?

00:09:00.310 --> 00:09:02.800
So we often ask
in studies, where

00:09:02.800 --> 00:09:04.890
we do an internal
discrimination studies,

00:09:04.890 --> 00:09:07.880
to tell us is the first or
second interval the longest?

00:09:07.880 --> 00:09:10.444
Google, please play music.

00:09:10.444 --> 00:09:12.280
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:09:12.280 --> 00:09:14.530
So there's a simple interval
discrimination task.

00:09:14.530 --> 00:09:16.840
And the question is, was
the first or second longest?

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:18.400
And the first was
100 milliseconds

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:21.100
and the second interval
was 150 milliseconds.

00:09:21.100 --> 00:09:24.130
Now, if you have some
timer in your brain

00:09:24.130 --> 00:09:26.932
that's fixed like a watch,
maybe it doesn't matter.

00:09:26.932 --> 00:09:28.390
Maybe you can't
get better at that.

00:09:28.390 --> 00:09:31.750
But if you practice and
that timer improves,

00:09:31.750 --> 00:09:33.700
then you should be
able to pick that up.

00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:34.900
And we do.

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:40.700
And we can tell here that in
the 100 millisecond case, that's

00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:43.370
what you just heard,
people improve dramatically

00:09:43.370 --> 00:09:45.140
with practice.

00:09:45.140 --> 00:09:47.540
But interestingly, if you
had a clock in your brain

00:09:47.540 --> 00:09:50.540
that was your master
clock, and that clock

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:52.750
with somehow improving,
you should get better

00:09:52.750 --> 00:09:53.519
at all intervals.

00:09:53.519 --> 00:09:56.060
So you should also get better
at the 50 millisecond interval,

00:09:56.060 --> 00:09:58.610
the 200 millisecond interval,
or the 500 millisecond.

00:09:58.610 --> 00:09:59.780
But you don't.

00:09:59.780 --> 00:10:01.340
So this is a bit strange.

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:04.130
It's almost as if you have
multiple clocks in your brain.

00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:06.170
You have an array
of different clocks

00:10:06.170 --> 00:10:10.340
that can tell time across
different time ranges.

00:10:10.340 --> 00:10:12.800
So how does the brain do that?

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:18.180
Or what parts of the brain
are responsible for time?

00:10:18.180 --> 00:10:20.600
Fortunately, we know exactly
what part of the brain

00:10:20.600 --> 00:10:21.560
tells time.

00:10:21.560 --> 00:10:23.710
And that's this part
right here, right

00:10:23.710 --> 00:10:27.650
beside locality and music,
conveniently located.

00:10:27.650 --> 00:10:30.150
This, of course, is nonsense.

00:10:30.150 --> 00:10:33.230
But this phrenological
view of time,

00:10:33.230 --> 00:10:37.001
nevertheless, is surprisingly
influential in how

00:10:37.001 --> 00:10:38.000
people think about time.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.326
So people do still think
about time, even today,

00:10:40.326 --> 00:10:42.950
in the sense that you might have
a central clock in your brain.

00:10:42.950 --> 00:10:44.690
So the office of this
faculty is to mark

00:10:44.690 --> 00:10:46.500
the passage of time,
duration, succession

00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:47.810
of events, et cetera.

00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:49.680
It also remembers dates,
keeps correct time

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:51.365
in music and
dancing, and induces

00:10:51.365 --> 00:10:54.680
to punctuality in the
fulfillment of engagement.

00:10:54.680 --> 00:10:56.120
So this is an
extreme view of what

00:10:56.120 --> 00:10:59.580
you'd call a central clock, or
a master clock, in your brain.

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:01.130
We know that this
is not correct.

00:11:01.130 --> 00:11:03.380
The brain has multiple
ways to tell time,

00:11:03.380 --> 00:11:06.260
has multiple areas
in the brain that

00:11:06.260 --> 00:11:09.170
are involved in telling time.

00:11:09.170 --> 00:11:11.660
To understand how
the brain tells time,

00:11:11.660 --> 00:11:17.790
let's first remind ourselves how
man-made clocks actually work.

00:11:17.790 --> 00:11:23.090
So man-made clocks,
despite their complexity,

00:11:23.090 --> 00:11:26.750
all work, for the most part,
on an embarrassingly simple

00:11:26.750 --> 00:11:27.650
principle.

00:11:27.650 --> 00:11:32.000
And that's just an oscillator,
your time base, and a counter.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.760
So whether you're talking about
a pendulum clock or a quartz

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:37.670
crystal or even an atomic
clock, in which you're

00:11:37.670 --> 00:11:43.010
using the period of the
electromagnetic vibrations

00:11:43.010 --> 00:11:45.440
to tell time,
you're just counting

00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:47.460
the ticks of an oscillator.

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:50.630
So it's reasonable to ask, is
that how the brain tells time?

00:11:50.630 --> 00:11:51.980
The answer is no.

00:11:51.980 --> 00:11:54.980
So as this quote from
Einstein reminds us,

00:11:54.980 --> 00:11:56.570
"Any physical
phenomenon may be used

00:11:56.570 --> 00:11:59.960
as a clock provided it can be
exactly repeated as many times

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:01.470
as desired."

00:12:01.470 --> 00:12:07.040
So here we have raindrops
falling on a pond.

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:10.460
And if I asked you, which
raindrop fell first, that one

00:12:10.460 --> 00:12:12.590
over here or down here?

00:12:12.590 --> 00:12:14.840
You could tell me this
raindrop fell first.

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:17.510
And if we were so inclined
and knew a bit of physics,

00:12:17.510 --> 00:12:19.310
we could even
calculate the interval.

00:12:19.310 --> 00:12:22.100
So the point is that
even this static image

00:12:22.100 --> 00:12:24.690
has information about time.

00:12:24.690 --> 00:12:28.100
And that's because physical
systems that have dynamics

00:12:28.100 --> 00:12:29.117
naturally tell time.

00:12:29.117 --> 00:12:30.950
I mean, that's essentially
what dynamics is.

00:12:30.950 --> 00:12:33.000
Dynamics is the change in time.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:37.070
So the idea is that the
brain uses its own dynamics

00:12:37.070 --> 00:12:38.870
as one way to tell time.

00:12:38.870 --> 00:12:44.390
So neurons are the computation
element of the brain.

00:12:44.390 --> 00:12:49.850
And neurons have their dendrites
and their axons down here.

00:12:49.850 --> 00:12:53.030
The axons of one
neuron can come over

00:12:53.030 --> 00:12:55.460
and synapse on the
dendrites of another neuron.

00:12:55.460 --> 00:12:57.170
And that's where
they make a synapse.

00:12:57.170 --> 00:13:00.890
It releases transmitter here and
creates a bioelectrical signal

00:13:00.890 --> 00:13:05.160
that travels towards the soma
of the post-synaptic nerve.

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:07.370
So if you have these
elements and they're

00:13:07.370 --> 00:13:10.420
connected to each other, one
way we could make a timer

00:13:10.420 --> 00:13:15.560
or a clock, if you will, is
to connect them in a chain.

00:13:15.560 --> 00:13:17.810
So if we had one neuron that
was connected to another,

00:13:17.810 --> 00:13:19.601
connected to another,
connected to another,

00:13:19.601 --> 00:13:21.770
connected to another,
we can now see

00:13:21.770 --> 00:13:24.582
that we'll have this
temporal pattern of activity

00:13:24.582 --> 00:13:27.040
in which one neuron activates
the next, activates the next,

00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:27.920
activates the next.

00:13:27.920 --> 00:13:30.650
So you know that, if
this neuron is active,

00:13:30.650 --> 00:13:35.480
that eight or nine time
units have elapsed.

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:38.780
So indeed, it seems that
one way the brain tells

00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:42.140
time on the scale of tens
to hundreds of milliseconds

00:13:42.140 --> 00:13:44.840
to seconds is through
neural dynamics.

00:13:47.630 --> 00:13:50.720
And we know this in
part due to research

00:13:50.720 --> 00:13:55.160
on a number of studies, on
both humans and animals.

00:13:55.160 --> 00:13:58.220
And one animal that knows how
to time very well are songbirds.

00:13:58.220 --> 00:14:01.850
So these are zebra
finches and they sing.

