00:17:12.859 --> 00:17:17.450
Now we all know that,
whatever the clocks that

00:17:17.450 --> 00:17:21.420
are within our brain, is
sometimes they're inaccurate.

00:17:21.420 --> 00:17:23.990
So there's a mismatch
between objective time

00:17:23.990 --> 00:17:25.940
and subjective time.

00:17:25.940 --> 00:17:29.090
And this leads to
temporal illusions

00:17:29.090 --> 00:17:30.570
or temporal distortions.

00:17:30.570 --> 00:17:34.010
Everybody is familiar with, time
flies when you're having fun.

00:17:34.010 --> 00:17:37.520
And to go back to a quote
from Henry James, which

00:17:37.520 --> 00:17:41.780
was from his magnum opus,
"Principles of Psychology,"

00:17:41.780 --> 00:17:43.310
written over 100 years ago.

00:17:43.310 --> 00:17:45.320
He says, "In general,
a time filled

00:17:45.320 --> 00:17:47.330
with varied and
interesting experiences

00:17:47.330 --> 00:17:50.600
seems short in passing,
but long as we look back.

00:17:50.600 --> 00:17:53.360
On the other hand, a tract
of time empty of experiences

00:17:53.360 --> 00:17:56.420
seems long in passing,
but in retrospect short."

00:17:56.420 --> 00:18:00.270
So some people refer to this
as the vacation paradox.

00:18:00.270 --> 00:18:03.680
You're having fun in
Athens for the first day

00:18:03.680 --> 00:18:08.060
and you're seeing a lot of
new sites, meeting new people,

00:18:08.060 --> 00:18:12.030
and time seems to
fly by prospectively.

00:18:12.030 --> 00:18:15.140
So as it's happening,
as it's playing out,

00:18:15.140 --> 00:18:19.160
prospectively your
estimates of time

00:18:19.160 --> 00:18:20.810
are only a short
amount of time has

00:18:20.810 --> 00:18:22.226
elapsed, even
though it might have

00:18:22.226 --> 00:18:24.320
been a long period of time.

00:18:24.320 --> 00:18:28.620
But retrospectively,
as you look back,

00:18:28.620 --> 00:18:31.770
that's not so much a timing
task but a memory task.

00:18:31.770 --> 00:18:33.780
You're thinking back
of the number of items,

00:18:33.780 --> 00:18:36.030
or you're influenced by the
number of items in memory.

00:18:36.030 --> 00:18:37.740
So if you have a
filled day in which

00:18:37.740 --> 00:18:40.410
a lot of interesting
things were happening,

00:18:40.410 --> 00:18:42.690
you're going to have a lot
of memories of that event

00:18:42.690 --> 00:18:44.760
and left with the
impression that it was

00:18:44.760 --> 00:18:47.070
a long period of time elapsing.

00:18:47.070 --> 00:18:52.200
Now in contrast, if
you're bored or anxious,

00:18:52.200 --> 00:18:57.570
then as time is going
by prospectively,

00:18:57.570 --> 00:18:59.540
you might overestimate
the amount of time.

00:18:59.540 --> 00:19:02.190
It seems like a lot of
time has been going by.

00:19:02.190 --> 00:19:05.460
So you're stuck at
the airport and you're

00:19:05.460 --> 00:19:11.040
on a six hour wait
because of a plane delay,

00:19:11.040 --> 00:19:12.570
and time is dragging.

00:19:12.570 --> 00:19:14.850
You're bored out of your mind.

00:19:14.850 --> 00:19:18.600
Retrospectively, when you
look back over your trip,

00:19:18.600 --> 00:19:22.590
that's merely a blip in
your conscious experiences.

00:19:22.590 --> 00:19:26.670
So because you know the Atlanta
bathroom is only so interesting

00:19:26.670 --> 00:19:29.070
and it didn't store
too much information

00:19:29.070 --> 00:19:34.090
about that wonderful experience
in your memory banks.

00:19:34.090 --> 00:19:37.620
So we have this paradox
between prospective timing

00:19:37.620 --> 00:19:42.480
and retrospective timing, which
in part influences our ability

00:19:42.480 --> 00:19:44.010
to tell time.

00:19:44.010 --> 00:19:47.490
Now everybody has
also known about cases

00:19:47.490 --> 00:19:52.350
under extreme danger
or extreme stress

00:19:52.350 --> 00:19:54.840
situations, in
which people report

00:19:54.840 --> 00:19:56.880
time actually slowing
down or things

00:19:56.880 --> 00:19:59.430
happening in slow motion.

00:19:59.430 --> 00:20:04.740
And so this is a report
of a race car driver

00:20:04.740 --> 00:20:07.500
whose car was thrown into the
air, spun around in the air.

00:20:07.500 --> 00:20:11.530
He obviously survived and
later gives this report.

00:20:11.530 --> 00:20:13.740
"It seemed like the
whole thing took forever.

00:20:13.740 --> 00:20:15.360
Everything was in
slow motion and it

00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:17.580
seemed to me like I was
a player on the stage

00:20:17.580 --> 00:20:20.460
and could see myself tumbling
over and over in the car.

00:20:20.460 --> 00:20:22.110
It was as though I
sat in the stands

00:20:22.110 --> 00:20:24.280
and saw it all happening."

00:20:24.280 --> 00:20:25.890
So here, obviously,
it's not only

00:20:25.890 --> 00:20:29.490
their impression of the passage
of time that is being altered,

00:20:29.490 --> 00:20:30.690
space as well.

00:20:30.690 --> 00:20:34.020
I think this is probably best
described as an hallucination.

00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:37.410
So this is an altered
state in which

00:20:37.410 --> 00:20:41.850
our sense of time and sense
of body, sense of space,

00:20:41.850 --> 00:20:43.140
has been dramatically altered.

00:20:43.140 --> 00:20:46.620
So I think the mystery
here is not so much

00:20:46.620 --> 00:20:48.330
what happens in these
states, but what

00:20:48.330 --> 00:20:50.220
happens in a normal
state that gives us

00:20:50.220 --> 00:20:55.290
our impression of
the passage of time.

00:20:55.290 --> 00:20:59.070
Now this ability to
tell time and perceive

00:20:59.070 --> 00:21:02.490
the passage of time, estimate
how much time has elapsed,

00:21:02.490 --> 00:21:05.190
is not unique to
humans in any way.

00:21:05.190 --> 00:21:07.140
All animals, or most
animals, certainly

00:21:07.140 --> 00:21:09.660
have that sense of
the time of day,

00:21:09.660 --> 00:21:11.670
they have a
circadian clock, they

00:21:11.670 --> 00:21:16.160
can learn when food will
arrive, and so forth.

00:21:16.160 --> 00:21:18.750
What is unique in
humans, however,

00:21:18.750 --> 00:21:21.090
is probably our ability
to engage in what

00:21:21.090 --> 00:21:23.140
we call Mental Time Travel.

00:21:23.140 --> 00:21:28.770
So we can think about the
past and relive our memories

00:21:28.770 --> 00:21:34.140
and re-experience things that
we have already experienced

00:21:34.140 --> 00:21:36.160
and sort of study that.

00:21:36.160 --> 00:21:39.510
We can learn, we can re-imagine
a conversation we had,

00:21:39.510 --> 00:21:42.420
we can give it alternate
endings to test out

00:21:42.420 --> 00:21:45.840
whether we should have said
something different or not.

00:21:45.840 --> 00:21:49.050
But even more importantly,
we can imagine the future.

00:21:49.050 --> 00:21:51.090
We can project ourselves
into the future

00:21:51.090 --> 00:21:53.440
and simulate the
future in our heads.

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:55.500
And some people believe
that this is indeed

00:21:55.500 --> 00:21:57.540
why consciousness evolved.

00:21:57.540 --> 00:22:00.690
So consciousness is a way
to simulate the future.

00:22:00.690 --> 00:22:04.920
And this is what
makes humans, humans.

00:22:04.920 --> 00:22:08.970
The first person to carve
a knife or a weapon out

00:22:08.970 --> 00:22:12.950
of an obsidian stone must
have had something in mind.

00:22:12.950 --> 00:22:14.700
What am I going to use this for?

00:22:14.700 --> 00:22:17.490
So this ability to
think about what

00:22:17.490 --> 00:22:19.650
this will be used
for in the future

00:22:19.650 --> 00:22:22.050
seems to evade the
ability of most animals.

00:22:22.050 --> 00:22:25.140
So you take one of the
most important inventions

00:22:25.140 --> 00:22:29.040
of humankind, agriculture,
it's a hard concept that we

00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:30.030
take for granted.

00:22:30.030 --> 00:22:31.890
I'm going to plant
something now and reap

00:22:31.890 --> 00:22:34.020
its benefits that are
going to guarantee survival

00:22:34.020 --> 00:22:35.520
a year from now.

00:22:35.520 --> 00:22:41.340
This ability to link
cause and effect actions

00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:44.890
across large delta T's,
long periods of time,

00:22:44.890 --> 00:22:46.590
is very unique to humans.

00:22:46.590 --> 00:22:49.140
I've always wondered if
humans are the only species

00:22:49.140 --> 00:22:51.210
to have figured out the
relationship between sex

00:22:51.210 --> 00:22:52.120
and pregnancy.

00:22:52.120 --> 00:22:55.090
That's a fairly
long period of time.

00:22:55.090 --> 00:22:57.210
Can other animals grasp
that relationship?

00:22:57.210 --> 00:23:01.620
Because it spans periods
of weeks or months.

00:23:01.620 --> 00:23:06.760
Now looking into the
future can be a bummer,

00:23:06.760 --> 00:23:11.560
because the first humans
to really see the future

00:23:11.560 --> 00:23:14.560
and grasp it, saw something
they probably didn't like.

00:23:14.560 --> 00:23:17.320
And this might have been,
by the way, a good time

00:23:17.320 --> 00:23:20.650
to invent religion, when you
first started understanding

00:23:20.650 --> 00:23:22.530
what the future holds.

00:23:22.530 --> 00:23:24.460
And I think this
point is beautifully

00:23:24.460 --> 00:23:30.070
made by Jorge Luis Borges, "To
be immortal is commonplace;

00:23:30.070 --> 00:23:32.570
except for man, all creatures
are immortal, for they

00:23:32.570 --> 00:23:34.030
are ignorant of death."

00:23:34.030 --> 00:23:38.470
So certainly seeing into
the long term future

00:23:38.470 --> 00:23:42.920
is what characterizes
our species in many ways.

00:23:42.920 --> 00:23:47.810
But it also does affect
our culture in many ways

00:23:47.810 --> 00:23:50.610
and how we cope
with what we see.

00:23:50.610 --> 00:23:57.430
Now just because humans
are uniquely able--

00:23:57.430 --> 00:23:59.670
and I'm sorry, there's
a going to be one more

