00:26:14.630 --> 00:26:22.520
So the major issue
there, of course,

00:26:22.520 --> 00:26:25.780
is that much of what
we do is contingent

00:26:25.780 --> 00:26:30.040
upon our understanding
that what we do now

00:26:30.040 --> 00:26:32.230
has consequences in the future.

00:26:32.230 --> 00:26:37.060
And going to school, saving
for retirement, exercising,

00:26:37.060 --> 00:26:39.850
are all things that we take
for granted but are implicitly

00:26:39.850 --> 00:26:45.070
contingent on our understanding
of temporal relationships,

00:26:45.070 --> 00:26:47.320
of long term temporal
relationships.

00:26:47.320 --> 00:26:51.460
But many of the problems we face
as individuals and as members

00:26:51.460 --> 00:26:54.940
of society arise from not
doing that well enough,

00:26:54.940 --> 00:26:56.180
Temporal Myopia.

00:26:56.180 --> 00:26:59.380
So personal credit card debt,
exercising and eating healthy,

00:26:59.380 --> 00:27:00.760
not saving enough
for retirement,

00:27:00.760 --> 00:27:02.980
are things at the
individual level which

00:27:02.980 --> 00:27:08.590
we struggle with in order
to balance our short term

00:27:08.590 --> 00:27:10.780
gratification with
long term rewards.

00:27:10.780 --> 00:27:14.680
At the more sort
of societal levels,

00:27:14.680 --> 00:27:17.290
failure to adjust climate
change, under funded pension

00:27:17.290 --> 00:27:21.130
plans, national debt, are things
that at the societal level

00:27:21.130 --> 00:27:23.590
emerge in part
because of our failure

00:27:23.590 --> 00:27:26.950
to take appropriate
actions in the present

00:27:26.950 --> 00:27:31.270
to assure or guarantee a better
quality of life or health

00:27:31.270 --> 00:27:33.140
in the future.

00:27:33.140 --> 00:27:37.030
Now humans, as I
said, are uniquely

00:27:37.030 --> 00:27:41.060
able to think about
the long term future.

00:27:41.060 --> 00:27:42.610
So how did that come about?

00:27:42.610 --> 00:27:46.540
What's unique about the human
brain that gives us the ability

00:27:46.540 --> 00:27:49.310
to understand the fundamental
difference between the past,

00:27:49.310 --> 00:27:53.090
present, and future and
to plan for months, years,

00:27:53.090 --> 00:27:55.750
or even decades ahead?

00:27:55.750 --> 00:28:01.240
So some people have argued
that we do that in part

00:28:01.240 --> 00:28:10.540
because of our ability
to talk and use language.

00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:13.880
and our brain's
ability to co-opt

00:28:13.880 --> 00:28:18.970
to the parts of the brain that
are used to understand space.

00:28:18.970 --> 00:28:22.670
The idea is that there's areas
in the brains of most mammals

00:28:22.670 --> 00:28:25.940
that allow them to navigate
and understand space,

00:28:25.940 --> 00:28:27.200
in a manner of speaking.

00:28:27.200 --> 00:28:30.980
And maybe the human brain
co-opted those same structures

00:28:30.980 --> 00:28:33.160
to allow us to understand time.

00:28:33.160 --> 00:28:36.050
And one argument
in favor of this

00:28:36.050 --> 00:28:41.360
is that a lot of the
ways we talk about time

00:28:41.360 --> 00:28:44.270
is by using spatial metaphors.

00:28:44.270 --> 00:28:46.940
So I might say,
it was a long day,

00:28:46.940 --> 00:28:49.280
or I'm looking
forward to the clips.

00:28:49.280 --> 00:28:52.220
Or you're thinking, I hope
this talk ends shortly.

00:28:52.220 --> 00:28:56.240
So we're using spatial
metaphors to talk about time.

00:29:01.730 --> 00:29:04.640
This idea of the
spatialization of time

00:29:04.640 --> 00:29:09.680
is really one of the main
ways we talk and discuss

00:29:09.680 --> 00:29:11.270
and understand time.

00:29:11.270 --> 00:29:14.150
And another way
to exemplify this

00:29:14.150 --> 00:29:17.000
is with what we call
the Wednesday question.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:18.740
So I'll say, our
Wednesday meeting

00:29:18.740 --> 00:29:21.830
was moved forward two days.

00:29:21.830 --> 00:29:24.110
What day is our meeting on?

00:29:24.110 --> 00:29:29.150
On Monday, or Friday?

00:29:29.150 --> 00:29:32.720
So there's no right
or wrong answer there,

00:29:32.720 --> 00:29:35.190
but it does reflect two
different perspectives

00:29:35.190 --> 00:29:37.310
we have about time.

00:29:37.310 --> 00:29:41.780
So if you view time
as sort of fixed

00:29:41.780 --> 00:29:45.740
and you're the one walking
through time and you're moving,

00:29:45.740 --> 00:29:48.240
then you'd say you
move something forward

00:29:48.240 --> 00:29:50.581
and from Wednesday it
might go to Friday.

00:29:50.581 --> 00:29:52.830
That's sort of what we call
an ego moving perspective.

00:29:52.830 --> 00:29:55.010
But if we have a time
moving perspective,

00:29:55.010 --> 00:29:58.760
you're probably in the Monday
group in which you're static

00:29:58.760 --> 00:30:03.980
and time is like a river
flowing towards you

00:30:03.980 --> 00:30:06.899
and then the meeting
would be on Monday.

00:30:06.899 --> 00:30:08.690
So there's these two
different perspectives

00:30:08.690 --> 00:30:10.910
that people have about time.

00:30:10.910 --> 00:30:13.130
And they just reflect
that ambiguity

00:30:13.130 --> 00:30:16.310
of language and the fact
that we spatialize time

00:30:16.310 --> 00:30:17.555
within our brains.

00:30:20.870 --> 00:30:24.350
Now this idea of the
spatialization of time,

00:30:24.350 --> 00:30:28.160
that time is laid
out in space, is

00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:34.710
very deep in the
philosophical literature,

00:30:34.710 --> 00:30:36.660
as well as in physics,
because there's

00:30:36.660 --> 00:30:40.920
sort of two diverging theories
as to the true nature of time.

00:30:40.920 --> 00:30:48.450
One is precisely this, that time
is a dimension much like space.

00:30:48.450 --> 00:30:50.500
So this is called eternalism.

00:30:53.040 --> 00:30:58.080
Under eternalism, the past,
the present, and the future

00:30:58.080 --> 00:31:00.580
are all equally real.

00:31:00.580 --> 00:31:02.830
Now is perfectly arbitrary.

00:31:02.830 --> 00:31:06.100
Now is as arbitrary as here.

00:31:06.100 --> 00:31:10.070
Just like here is a perfectly
valid point in space to be,

00:31:10.070 --> 00:31:12.790
I'm perfectly fine with
you being over there.

00:31:12.790 --> 00:31:16.460
In time, now is arbitrary and
I should be perfectly fine.

00:31:16.460 --> 00:31:19.240
In eternalism, now is
perfectly arbitrary

00:31:19.240 --> 00:31:22.420
and other versions of me
or other versions of you,

00:31:22.420 --> 00:31:25.580
if you will, are at past
moments or present moments.

00:31:25.580 --> 00:31:27.730
So everything is equally real.

00:31:27.730 --> 00:31:30.460
And under presentism,
in contrast, and this

00:31:30.460 --> 00:31:32.670
is sort of the more
intuitive sense we have,

00:31:32.670 --> 00:31:35.330
in that only the
present is real.

00:31:35.330 --> 00:31:37.630
So the past was real,
some configuration

00:31:37.630 --> 00:31:40.510
of the universe that we call
past and now exists only

00:31:40.510 --> 00:31:43.360
in our memories, was real.

00:31:43.360 --> 00:31:44.500
The present is real.

00:31:44.500 --> 00:31:46.720
And the future, or
some configuration

00:31:46.720 --> 00:31:48.460
of the universe at
some future point,

00:31:48.460 --> 00:31:52.010
will become real based on
what's happening in the present.

00:31:52.010 --> 00:31:56.950
So of course, eternalism sort
of justifies a talk or a debate

00:31:56.950 --> 00:31:59.397
about whether time
travel is possible.

00:31:59.397 --> 00:32:01.480
It has nothing do with the
physics of time travel,

00:32:01.480 --> 00:32:03.190
whether you can
actually do it or not,

00:32:03.190 --> 00:32:07.870
but eternalism justifies the
debate because at least there's

00:32:07.870 --> 00:32:10.390
moments in time that exist
that you could potentially

00:32:10.390 --> 00:32:11.930
try to travel to.

00:32:11.930 --> 00:32:14.350
Under presentism the
talk of time travel

00:32:14.350 --> 00:32:17.410
is a moot point because
there's nowhere to go,

00:32:17.410 --> 00:32:20.740
or there's no when to
go, to be more precise.

00:32:20.740 --> 00:32:25.660
Now eternalism is
sort of, to the degree

00:32:25.660 --> 00:32:29.680
that there is a standard view in
physics, is the standard view.

00:32:29.680 --> 00:32:36.250
And this is in part because
of Einstein's theory

00:32:36.250 --> 00:32:38.000
of special relativity.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:44.470
So let me just try to
convey, I find presentism

00:32:44.470 --> 00:32:45.670
to be much more intuitive.

00:32:45.670 --> 00:32:49.720
I think it's more consistent
with our experience.

00:32:49.720 --> 00:32:53.950
But we believe in eternalism,
at least in the physical sense,

00:32:53.950 --> 00:32:54.956
for very good reasons.

00:32:54.956 --> 00:32:56.830
So let me try to convey
those reasons, or one

00:32:56.830 --> 00:32:58.550
of those reasons.

00:32:58.550 --> 00:33:04.150
So to do this, let me go
over a thought experiment,

00:33:04.150 --> 00:33:06.970
an Einsteinian thought
experiment, in which

00:33:06.970 --> 00:33:10.120
we have the following setup.

00:33:10.120 --> 00:33:15.250
We have an observer on a
stationary platform and a train

00:33:15.250 --> 00:33:20.920
going by at a ludicrously,
impossibly fast speed of 2/3

00:33:20.920 --> 00:33:24.509
the speed of light, 0.67
times the speed of light.

00:33:24.509 --> 00:33:26.800
There's an individual in the
middle of the train that's

00:33:26.800 --> 00:33:30.880
shooting these space-age
bullets towards the front

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:33.400
and the back of the train.

00:33:33.400 --> 00:33:36.400
Now if you're this
individual, it

00:33:36.400 --> 00:33:39.970
doesn't matter, because
of the laws of physics

00:33:39.970 --> 00:33:43.060
and relativity, that
you're moving or not.

00:33:43.060 --> 00:33:45.340
So you're going to shoot
the bullet forward and shoot

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:47.590
the bullet backwards
and those bullets

00:33:47.590 --> 00:33:50.380
have to travel the same
distance at the same speed.

00:33:50.380 --> 00:33:52.960
So this pane of glass will
break at the same time

00:33:52.960 --> 00:33:53.950
as that pane of glass.

00:33:57.430 --> 00:34:00.050
So this person should observe
that pane of glass breaking

00:34:00.050 --> 00:34:01.550
at the same time
as this person was.

00:34:01.550 --> 00:34:05.000
Now here you're the
observer and you're

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.910
going to see the train
traveling at a high speed.

00:34:07.910 --> 00:34:10.040
You're going to see
this bullet traveling

00:34:10.040 --> 00:34:12.860
in the opposite direction
at the same speed.

00:34:12.860 --> 00:34:14.659
So this bullet will
have speed zero,

00:34:14.659 --> 00:34:17.400
it will have velocity zero.

00:34:17.400 --> 00:34:21.900
So basically, this bullet
will standing in mid-air

00:34:21.900 --> 00:34:24.690
as the back of the train
runs into the bullet.

00:34:24.690 --> 00:34:26.920
OK, that's pretty
straightforward.

00:34:26.920 --> 00:34:28.770
Now this forward
bullet should be

00:34:28.770 --> 00:34:33.170
going at the speed of the bullet
plus the speed of the train.

00:34:33.170 --> 00:34:35.840
Now the speed of the bullet
is 2/3 the speed of light,

00:34:35.840 --> 00:34:37.949
the speed of the train is
2/3 the speed of light.

00:34:37.949 --> 00:34:44.239
So the sum of those is 1.3
times the speed of light.

00:34:44.239 --> 00:34:45.290
That's a no-no, right?

00:34:45.290 --> 00:34:47.081
We can't go faster than
the speed of light,

00:34:47.081 --> 00:34:48.590
that's what Einstein told us.

00:34:48.590 --> 00:34:50.989
So there's something goofy
that's going to happen here.

00:34:50.989 --> 00:34:53.179
This bullet can't
be traveling as fast

00:34:53.179 --> 00:34:57.470
as it needs to be going to
break this pane of glass

00:34:57.470 --> 00:34:58.680
at the same time.

00:34:58.680 --> 00:35:03.830
So we see the bullet in motion
approaching the panes of glass.

00:35:03.830 --> 00:35:10.370
And the person on the train
will observe both panes breaking

00:35:10.370 --> 00:35:14.060
at the same time, they'll
be breaking simultaneously.

00:35:14.060 --> 00:35:17.090
But the person on the
stationary platform

00:35:17.090 --> 00:35:18.530
will not see that happen.

00:35:18.530 --> 00:35:21.170
And it has nothing
to do with delays

00:35:21.170 --> 00:35:24.700
or the time it takes information
to get from here to there.

00:35:24.700 --> 00:35:28.970
So it is just based on all
those adjustments and delays

00:35:28.970 --> 00:35:31.620
being taken into account.

00:35:31.620 --> 00:35:34.800
So this person will observe
a different reality.

00:35:34.800 --> 00:35:38.520
While this person has a reality
in which both panes of glass

00:35:38.520 --> 00:35:41.844
break at the same time,
for this person's reality,

00:35:41.844 --> 00:35:44.010
there will be a moment in
time where this is broken,

00:35:44.010 --> 00:35:46.110
but that is not.

00:35:46.110 --> 00:35:49.180
So this is taken as
an argument, this lack

00:35:49.180 --> 00:35:50.710
of absolute
simultaneity is taken

00:35:50.710 --> 00:35:55.372
as an argument for the block
universe, or for eternalism.

00:35:58.030 --> 00:35:58.870
Why is that?

00:35:58.870 --> 00:36:00.820
So let me give it again,
run that through you

00:36:00.820 --> 00:36:02.270
with this example here.

00:36:02.270 --> 00:36:06.610
So let's look at this sort
of mini block universe

00:36:06.610 --> 00:36:07.540
with four dimensions.

00:36:07.540 --> 00:36:09.970
But we're going to only plot
two, instead of the three

00:36:09.970 --> 00:36:11.860
spatial dimensions
we only have one,

00:36:11.860 --> 00:36:13.970
and we have this
temporal dimension.

00:36:13.970 --> 00:36:16.840
So for the person
on the train, this

00:36:16.840 --> 00:36:18.560
is their plane of simultaneity.

00:36:18.560 --> 00:36:21.611
There's a moment where
both panes of glass

00:36:21.611 --> 00:36:23.860
at the back of the train and
at the front of the train

00:36:23.860 --> 00:36:25.480
are both intact.

00:36:25.480 --> 00:36:28.150
There's another moment in
exactly the same moment where

00:36:28.150 --> 00:36:30.880
both panes of glass break.

00:36:30.880 --> 00:36:32.740
Then there'll be
another moment in time

00:36:32.740 --> 00:36:35.530
where both panes of
glass are already broken.

00:36:35.530 --> 00:36:38.894
So these are the
planes of simultaneity

00:36:38.894 --> 00:36:40.060
for the person on the train.

00:36:44.730 --> 00:36:48.880
In reality, the person on the
platform is, in our analogy,

00:36:48.880 --> 00:36:51.610
not moving, which is the same
thing as from the perspective

00:36:51.610 --> 00:36:53.520
of the person on the train.

00:36:53.520 --> 00:36:55.030
The person on the
platform is moving

00:36:55.030 --> 00:36:56.113
in the opposite direction.

00:36:56.113 --> 00:36:58.450
So just for reasons here,
this might be a bit easier

00:36:58.450 --> 00:36:59.620
to explain that way.

00:36:59.620 --> 00:37:01.510
So the person on
the platform is sort

00:37:01.510 --> 00:37:04.110
of traveling in the
opposite direction

00:37:04.110 --> 00:37:06.850
of the person on the train.

00:37:06.850 --> 00:37:11.710
Now these planes of
simultaneity don't match up

00:37:11.710 --> 00:37:14.060
for the person on the platform.

00:37:14.060 --> 00:37:17.990
So the plane of simultaneity,
Einstein's theory

00:37:17.990 --> 00:37:20.860
of special relativity
tells us that these moments

00:37:20.860 --> 00:37:23.761
will be the same on
this person's clock.

00:37:23.761 --> 00:37:26.260
So there will be a moment where
the front pain is not broken

00:37:26.260 --> 00:37:28.120
and the back one is.

00:37:28.120 --> 00:37:32.770
So the point is that it's as
if the universe, everything

00:37:32.770 --> 00:37:35.450
that can happen has
already happened.

00:37:35.450 --> 00:37:37.540
And the reason some
things appear simultaneous

00:37:37.540 --> 00:37:39.310
for one person and
not for another

00:37:39.310 --> 00:37:41.900
is a question of perspective.

00:37:41.900 --> 00:37:45.070
So here the idea is, from
this person's perspective,

00:37:45.070 --> 00:37:47.390
these events are aligned,
but not for this person.

00:37:47.390 --> 00:37:51.670
So this is one of the arguments
for eternalism or the block

00:37:51.670 --> 00:37:53.350
universe.

00:37:53.350 --> 00:37:55.600
Now there's a clash here, right?

00:37:55.600 --> 00:37:58.960
If this is true, it sort
of leaves our impression

00:37:58.960 --> 00:38:02.620
of the flow of time
as an illusion.

00:38:02.620 --> 00:38:05.210
Because if everything
has already happened,

00:38:05.210 --> 00:38:09.010
the clear subjective
feeling that time is flowing

00:38:09.010 --> 00:38:12.730
would seem that it has to be an
illusion, in a certain sense.

00:38:12.730 --> 00:38:16.450
And physicists have
long been aware of this.

00:38:16.450 --> 00:38:18.970
So this is a quote
from Roger Penrose,

00:38:18.970 --> 00:38:22.960
"It seems to me that there
are severe discrepancies

00:38:22.960 --> 00:38:24.400
between what we
consciously feel,

00:38:24.400 --> 00:38:26.320
concerning the flow
of time, and what

00:38:26.320 --> 00:38:29.712
our theories assert about the
reality of the physical world."

00:38:29.712 --> 00:38:31.420
Here's another good
quote by Herman Veil,

00:38:31.420 --> 00:38:36.280
a physicist from the mid 1900s.

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:39.760
"The objective world simply
is, it does not happen.

00:38:39.760 --> 00:38:41.500
Only to the gaze of
my consciousness,

00:38:41.500 --> 00:38:43.880
crawling upward along the
world line of my body,

00:38:43.880 --> 00:38:45.730
does a section of the
world come to life

00:38:45.730 --> 00:38:47.980
as a fleeting image
in space which

00:38:47.980 --> 00:38:49.750
continuously changes in time."

00:38:49.750 --> 00:38:53.290
So they're getting to this
issue that the flow of time

00:38:53.290 --> 00:38:54.610
must be an illusion.

00:38:54.610 --> 00:38:58.600
So this severely clashes with
the neuroscience of time.

00:38:58.600 --> 00:39:03.610
And it clearly feels that the
subjective experience of time

00:39:03.610 --> 00:39:04.440
is flowing by.

00:39:07.450 --> 00:39:13.960
Now the question is if this is
consistent with our experience

00:39:13.960 --> 00:39:14.829
of consciousness.

00:39:14.829 --> 00:39:16.620
Now we don't really
know what consciousness

00:39:16.620 --> 00:39:20.650
is so this is a very
difficult question to address.

00:39:20.650 --> 00:39:24.670
But consciousness
probably isn't what

00:39:24.670 --> 00:39:27.850
it seems to be, in the
sense that it seems

00:39:27.850 --> 00:39:31.510
to be providing a linear
narrative of what's happening

00:39:31.510 --> 00:39:34.720
in the world around us.

00:39:34.720 --> 00:39:37.690
Rather, the
unconscious mind seems

00:39:37.690 --> 00:39:41.410
to be creating this
narrative in chunks

00:39:41.410 --> 00:39:43.900
and then feeding this
into the conscious mind,

00:39:43.900 --> 00:39:46.780
or creating conscious
mind, if you will,

00:39:46.780 --> 00:39:51.280
to create a convenient and
apparent flow of what's

00:39:51.280 --> 00:39:52.190
happening.

00:39:52.190 --> 00:39:54.190
So there's a couple of
illusions that show this.

00:39:54.190 --> 00:39:56.260
It's a bit of a hard
concept to explain.

00:39:56.260 --> 00:39:58.840
But let me just try to give
you a quick example here.

00:39:58.840 --> 00:40:01.390
I'm going to say two
sentences and just

00:40:01.390 --> 00:40:04.300
pay attention to the
meaning of the sentences.

00:40:04.300 --> 00:40:07.000
So the first sentence
is, the mouse pad

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:09.030
was beside the computer.

00:40:09.030 --> 00:40:12.760
The second sentence,
the mouse was hungry.

00:40:12.760 --> 00:40:15.820
So in both those sentences,
the meaning of the word mouse

00:40:15.820 --> 00:40:17.080
was very different, right?

00:40:17.080 --> 00:40:18.940
So I think you're
able to understand

00:40:18.940 --> 00:40:21.190
that in the first case
the mouse referred

00:40:21.190 --> 00:40:24.160
to an object, the
computer mouse pad.

00:40:24.160 --> 00:40:27.730
And the second to a rodent.

00:40:27.730 --> 00:40:29.260
But the meaning of
mouse could only

00:40:29.260 --> 00:40:31.540
be determined by the
words that came after.

00:40:31.540 --> 00:40:35.500
You cannot possibly interpret
that sentence in real time.

00:40:35.500 --> 00:40:39.610
The mouse pad or the
mouse was hungry.

00:40:39.610 --> 00:40:43.810
So what comes after has to
influence your interpretation

00:40:43.810 --> 00:40:45.740
of what came before.

00:40:45.740 --> 00:40:47.920
So this is one of
the lines of evidence

00:40:47.920 --> 00:40:51.190
that suggests that our
conscious experience is not

00:40:51.190 --> 00:40:53.950
so much a continuous
linear flow of the world

00:40:53.950 --> 00:41:00.020
around us, but of a
creation that is generated

00:41:00.020 --> 00:41:05.420
and sort of fits in bursts of
the interpretation of what's

00:41:05.420 --> 00:41:07.220
happening around us.

00:41:07.220 --> 00:41:11.750
So it may be the case that our
understanding of consciousness

00:41:11.750 --> 00:41:15.320
may or may not be compatible
with the standard view

00:41:15.320 --> 00:41:16.370
in physics.

00:41:16.370 --> 00:41:20.720
I think Steven Pinker was
hinting at this when he stated,

00:41:20.720 --> 00:41:23.540
"Matter is extended in space,
but consciousness exists

00:41:23.540 --> 00:41:28.090
in time as surely as it proceeds
from 'I think' to 'I am.'"

00:41:28.090 --> 00:41:31.385
So we have to decide--

00:41:31.385 --> 00:41:33.410
and I think physicists
and neuroscientists

00:41:33.410 --> 00:41:39.140
have to collaborate more
to decide if we should view

00:41:39.140 --> 00:41:42.320
our subjective sense
of the passage of time

00:41:42.320 --> 00:41:46.370
as an empirical observation
about the universe, one that

00:41:46.370 --> 00:41:48.740
has to be explained by physics.

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:51.260
Or if it's an illusion
in the deepest

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:53.344
sense of the world,
and thus one that

00:41:53.344 --> 00:41:55.010
doesn't have to be
explained by physics,

00:41:55.010 --> 00:41:57.470
but then has to be
explained by neuroscience.

00:41:57.470 --> 00:42:00.680
How does the brain generate the
conscious, subjective feeling

00:42:00.680 --> 00:42:02.810
of something that
has no correlate

00:42:02.810 --> 00:42:07.100
in the physical world, that
is, of the flow of time?

00:42:07.100 --> 00:42:13.479
Now to address
these questions, I

00:42:13.479 --> 00:42:14.770
think we have a long way to go.

00:42:14.770 --> 00:42:19.300
And neuroscience is
a very unique field.

00:42:19.300 --> 00:42:22.810
Neuroscience a unique
field in all of sciences

00:42:22.810 --> 00:42:24.430
because neuroscience
is the only field

00:42:24.430 --> 00:42:27.760
in which the organ, or
the thing being studied,

00:42:27.760 --> 00:42:29.980
is also doing the studying.

00:42:29.980 --> 00:42:32.760
And this raises a couple
of potential concerns.

00:42:32.760 --> 00:42:34.810
Not least of which, well,
is that even possible?

00:42:34.810 --> 00:42:38.290
Can something understand itself?

00:42:38.290 --> 00:42:43.150
It's of course way too early
to answer that question.

00:42:43.150 --> 00:42:46.210
But as scientific fields
evolve, as they mature,

00:42:46.210 --> 00:42:49.000
part of that
maturation process is

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:51.910
to progressively embrace time.

00:42:51.910 --> 00:42:54.760
You look at what I would
consider the first field

00:42:54.760 --> 00:42:57.400
of modern science, geometry.

00:42:57.400 --> 00:43:02.440
Geometry is formalized by
Euclid 2,300 years ago,

00:43:02.440 --> 00:43:04.720
it was highly influential
and transformative.

00:43:04.720 --> 00:43:06.790
But why was it the
first field of science?

00:43:06.790 --> 00:43:08.740
Well, it was the
first field of science

00:43:08.740 --> 00:43:12.339
because science is easier
if you can ignore time.

00:43:12.339 --> 00:43:13.630
That's what geometry is, right?

00:43:13.630 --> 00:43:16.420
Geometry is the study
of space and objects

00:43:16.420 --> 00:43:18.430
that don't change in time.

00:43:18.430 --> 00:43:21.760
It was only around
2,000 years after Euclid

00:43:21.760 --> 00:43:25.870
when people, such as
Galileo and Newton

00:43:25.870 --> 00:43:32.289
came along, and fully integrated
time and dynamics into physics.

00:43:32.289 --> 00:43:33.205
Same thing in biology.

00:43:33.205 --> 00:43:36.440
If you think about biology, up
until 1700s, most of the 1800s,

00:43:36.440 --> 00:43:40.840
it was largely taxonomic
and fairly static.

00:43:40.840 --> 00:43:43.690
And then Darwin, playing
the role of Galileo,

00:43:43.690 --> 00:43:46.390
said, hey, species are dynamic.

00:43:46.390 --> 00:43:49.480
They change, they adapt,
they evolve in time.

00:43:49.480 --> 00:43:52.450
I think neuroscience is only
reaching this renaissance

00:43:52.450 --> 00:43:55.330
now where it's fully
beginning to embrace time.

00:43:55.330 --> 00:43:58.930
And realize that the brain is,
in a sense, a temporal organ.

00:43:58.930 --> 00:44:00.610
It's a time machine,
if you will.

00:44:00.610 --> 00:44:03.210
It tells time, it remembers
the past to predict the future,

00:44:03.210 --> 00:44:05.020
it allows us to
mentally time travel,

00:44:05.020 --> 00:44:08.350
and creates the subjective
sense of the flow of time.

00:44:08.350 --> 00:44:11.620
So elucidating how the brain
tells time, represents,

00:44:11.620 --> 00:44:14.500
and conceptualizes time is
critical to understanding

00:44:14.500 --> 00:44:17.980
the human mind and the
nature of consciousness.

00:44:17.980 --> 00:44:19.205
Thank you very much.

