Because it was
evolutionarily adaptable

00:53:17.080 --> 00:53:18.600
it was like a good thing for us.

00:53:18.600 --> 00:53:21.799
Do you think time could be
something similar to that?

00:53:21.799 --> 00:53:24.090
DEAN BUONOMANO: So there's
this very interesting debate

00:53:24.090 --> 00:53:26.580
about whether time--

00:53:26.580 --> 00:53:31.220
So some fields or
hypotheses in physics

00:53:31.220 --> 00:53:36.030
are trying to get rid of time,
so say that time doesn't exist.

00:53:36.030 --> 00:53:39.750
And what this means is that
time is not a property.

00:53:39.750 --> 00:53:42.330
They're not saying that time,
clock time, doesn't exist.

00:53:42.330 --> 00:53:45.870
What they're saying is that time
isn't a fundamental property

00:53:45.870 --> 00:53:49.470
of the universe, it's not
like energy or matter,

00:53:49.470 --> 00:53:51.691
and that time is simply an
abstraction, a creation,

00:53:51.691 --> 00:53:52.440
of the human mind.

00:53:52.440 --> 00:53:55.560
The way Ernst Mach put this
is, it's utterly impossible

00:53:55.560 --> 00:53:57.990
to measure change
by time because time

00:53:57.990 --> 00:54:02.100
is an abstraction at which we
arrive at by measuring change.

00:54:02.100 --> 00:54:03.750
And that's indeed
what clocks do.

00:54:03.750 --> 00:54:07.860
All clocks are are just
some weights, some device,

00:54:07.860 --> 00:54:10.830
that conveniently
standardizes change,

00:54:10.830 --> 00:54:14.820
whether that change is the
swing of a pendulum or a quartz

00:54:14.820 --> 00:54:15.570
crystal.

00:54:15.570 --> 00:54:18.900
So the subjective
feeling of time,

00:54:18.900 --> 00:54:22.050
I think I've sort of already
expressed, it's unknown.

00:54:22.050 --> 00:54:26.190
But the concept of
time, I do like the idea

00:54:26.190 --> 00:54:27.720
that it's an
abstraction that we've

00:54:27.720 --> 00:54:30.480
created that's
incredibly useful to help

00:54:30.480 --> 00:54:34.120
us understand the universe
and make sense of the world.

00:54:34.120 --> 00:54:36.466
But it's not a fundamental
property of physics.

00:54:36.466 --> 00:54:39.999
AUDIENCE: Yeah, thank you.

00:54:39.999 --> 00:54:41.790
AUDIENCE: Thanks for
this talk, by the way.

00:54:41.790 --> 00:54:43.037
DEAN BUONOMANO: Thank you.

00:54:43.037 --> 00:54:45.120
AUDIENCE: I had some
questions about your thoughts

00:54:45.120 --> 00:54:51.240
on how our relative
conceptions of time

00:54:51.240 --> 00:54:54.840
are limited by physical
dendrites, axons,

00:54:54.840 --> 00:54:56.660
physical barriers.

00:54:56.660 --> 00:54:59.130
So in a world where
we are able to create

00:54:59.130 --> 00:55:02.040
artificial intelligence,
or even potentially upload

00:55:02.040 --> 00:55:04.770
our own consciousness, or
replicate our consciousness,

00:55:04.770 --> 00:55:12.060
in a world which isn't limited
by dendrites and axons,

00:55:12.060 --> 00:55:15.240
what are your thoughts
on being able to extend

00:55:15.240 --> 00:55:19.650
our concepts of time because
of those physical barriers

00:55:19.650 --> 00:55:20.340
removed?

00:55:20.340 --> 00:55:21.640
Or slowing down.

00:55:21.640 --> 00:55:24.450
So a real person is
existing, there's

00:55:24.450 --> 00:55:27.780
an AI which experiences
1,000 years of time

00:55:27.780 --> 00:55:30.689
because they're able to
process information faster.

00:55:30.689 --> 00:55:32.730
DEAN BUONOMANO: There's
a couple of issues there.

00:55:32.730 --> 00:55:34.650
So those are deep questions.

00:55:34.650 --> 00:55:36.330
One is the hardware
question, right?

00:55:36.330 --> 00:55:39.210
Is consciousness in our
subjective experience

00:55:39.210 --> 00:55:42.210
of time hardware dependent,
hardware limited?

00:55:42.210 --> 00:55:47.250
Can you create AIs
that have consciousness

00:55:47.250 --> 00:55:49.200
totally equivalent to ours?

00:55:49.200 --> 00:55:51.210
So that's a question
that, of course,

00:55:51.210 --> 00:55:52.710
nobody knows the answer to.

00:55:52.710 --> 00:55:54.870
As a materialist,
I certainly believe

00:55:54.870 --> 00:55:56.790
there's no reason
that consciousness

00:55:56.790 --> 00:55:58.770
has to be hardware limited.

00:55:58.770 --> 00:56:02.640
Now that question, however,
is different from the question

00:56:02.640 --> 00:56:05.100
of speed of processing.

00:56:05.100 --> 00:56:08.040
So this question
of sampling rate

00:56:08.040 --> 00:56:11.390
in which the speed of processing
is ultimately independent

00:56:11.390 --> 00:56:13.270
of our notion of
the passage of time.

00:56:13.270 --> 00:56:17.610
You're processing signals
coming from my speech.

00:56:17.610 --> 00:56:19.560
You're doing that
right now that are far

00:56:19.560 --> 00:56:22.980
beyond your
subjective experience

00:56:22.980 --> 00:56:24.180
of the passage of time.

00:56:24.180 --> 00:56:26.010
So the brain clearly
processes things

00:56:26.010 --> 00:56:28.015
that are happening
very quickly like this,

00:56:28.015 --> 00:56:28.890
that's micro-seconds.

00:56:28.890 --> 00:56:31.270
Your brain detects that.

00:56:31.270 --> 00:56:32.910
So even though they're
made of neurons,

00:56:32.910 --> 00:56:34.201
it's an incredible feat, right?

00:56:34.201 --> 00:56:37.099
Neurons have a time constant
of maybe an action potential.

00:56:37.099 --> 00:56:39.390
So if you we're going to give
it a computer clock rate,

00:56:39.390 --> 00:56:41.850
you'd probably give
it a kilohertz instead

00:56:41.850 --> 00:56:46.140
of a couple of hundred
gigahertz, for example.

00:56:48.820 --> 00:56:50.827
So that time level
of processing is

00:56:50.827 --> 00:56:53.160
different from the time level
of subjective experiences.

00:56:53.160 --> 00:56:55.500
Now, nobody knows the
answer to the question

00:56:55.500 --> 00:57:01.110
of whether an AI
would be able to have

00:57:01.110 --> 00:57:03.690
these temporal distortions
of conscious experiences

00:57:03.690 --> 00:57:04.530
like you or I have.

00:57:04.530 --> 00:57:09.280
But I think there's, in a
way it's a wrong question.

00:57:09.280 --> 00:57:11.610
I think the mystery
is not so much

00:57:11.610 --> 00:57:16.860
how time comes to be distorted
in extreme cases of time

00:57:16.860 --> 00:57:18.930
dilation or time
compression, but what

00:57:18.930 --> 00:57:20.550
our normal sense of time is.

00:57:20.550 --> 00:57:23.530
And I view this as just the
flexibility of consciousness.

00:57:23.530 --> 00:57:26.280
You can be conscious of
a short period of time

00:57:26.280 --> 00:57:27.570
or a long period of time.

00:57:27.570 --> 00:57:29.160
That's just a
conscious state, it's

00:57:29.160 --> 00:57:30.660
just a flavor of
consciousness, just

00:57:30.660 --> 00:57:33.160
like pain or pleasure or color.

00:57:33.160 --> 00:57:35.760
So I think that
when we understand

00:57:35.760 --> 00:57:38.460
the nature of
consciousness, the question

00:57:38.460 --> 00:57:40.890
of whether it
seems long or short

00:57:40.890 --> 00:57:44.710
will be sort of a minor
issue along those lines.

00:57:44.710 --> 00:57:49.246
Because I think what we
perceive is a bit arbitrary.

00:57:49.246 --> 00:57:51.870
CARL: Just a quick note, we're
a bit over 2:00 PM, so let's not

00:57:51.870 --> 00:57:53.150
add more questions.

00:57:53.150 --> 00:57:55.964
If you're already in
line, ask your questions.

00:57:55.964 --> 00:57:57.380
AUDIENCE: OK, I
think you'll hear.

00:57:57.380 --> 00:57:59.570
I want to ask about,
what is the difference

00:57:59.570 --> 00:58:05.330
or are they the same thing for
the things like retrospective

00:58:05.330 --> 00:58:08.260
thinking and the
autobiographic memory?

00:58:08.260 --> 00:58:12.800
Or the retrospective thinking is
about a general loss of memory

00:58:12.800 --> 00:58:14.989
or just things about
myself in the past?

00:58:14.989 --> 00:58:16.780
DEAN BUONOMANO: Yes
that's a good question.

00:58:16.780 --> 00:58:20.900
So autobiographical
memory, or episodic memory,

00:58:20.900 --> 00:58:23.190
is about events in our own life.

00:58:23.190 --> 00:58:25.910
And that's tightly coupled
to how we retrospectively

00:58:25.910 --> 00:58:26.690
perceive time.

00:58:26.690 --> 00:58:28.190
So if there's a
period of time which

00:58:28.190 --> 00:58:30.260
you have a rich
autobiographical memory,

00:58:30.260 --> 00:58:32.360
I did this, this, this
this, this and this,

00:58:32.360 --> 00:58:36.410
that's likely to elicit
a long estimate of time.

00:58:36.410 --> 00:58:39.950
Whereas if you don't have
any events in memory,

00:58:39.950 --> 00:58:41.360
that's a short period of time.

00:58:41.360 --> 00:58:44.990
The extreme example of this
is somebody who has amnesia.

00:58:44.990 --> 00:58:48.470
So you can imagine if
somebody has no ability

00:58:48.470 --> 00:58:52.340
to form new episodic memories
or autobiographical memories,

00:58:52.340 --> 00:58:55.750
how could they even estimate
that time has elapsed?

00:58:55.750 --> 00:58:58.610
So there's this very
touching, poignant case

00:58:58.610 --> 00:59:01.520
of a British man
called Clive Waring.

00:59:01.520 --> 00:59:04.560
And maybe some of you
have seen specials on him.

00:59:04.560 --> 00:59:08.300
But he has terrible
anterograde amnesia

00:59:08.300 --> 00:59:12.030
and he seems to be
locked into the present.

00:59:12.030 --> 00:59:14.900
There's a story where he's
writing in his diary 9:00 AM,

00:59:14.900 --> 00:59:16.240
I just woke up.

00:59:16.240 --> 00:59:18.740
9:30, now I'm awake
for the first time.

00:59:18.740 --> 00:59:21.800
10 o'clock, now I'm really
awake for the first time.

00:59:21.800 --> 00:59:23.870
Because if you don't
have that memory, how can

00:59:23.870 --> 00:59:25.370
how much time has elapsed?

00:59:25.370 --> 00:59:28.970
So clearly, retrospectively,
time and memory

00:59:28.970 --> 00:59:29.818
are tightly coupled.

00:59:33.410 --> 00:59:35.810
AUDIENCE: So as you said, all
of our time keeping devices

00:59:35.810 --> 00:59:38.660
rely on oscillators,
or rely on some kind

00:59:38.660 --> 00:59:40.100
of notion of periodicity.

00:59:40.100 --> 00:59:45.129
And so I guess my
question is if you

00:59:45.129 --> 00:59:46.670
look at an oscillation
or a sine wave

00:59:46.670 --> 00:59:49.910
or any sort of any
sort of phenomenon

00:59:49.910 --> 00:59:51.390
that you can
understand that way,

00:59:51.390 --> 00:59:52.940
there's a notion
of symmetry that's

00:59:52.940 --> 00:59:54.890
really important,
that you could be

00:59:54.890 --> 00:59:57.710
at one point in this
oscillation or you

00:59:57.710 --> 01:00:00.800
can be at the exact same
point in another period later.

01:00:00.800 --> 01:00:03.890
And so it gives you that
eternal perspective.

01:00:03.890 --> 01:00:05.400
What if that didn't exist?

01:00:05.400 --> 01:00:08.600
So how would we measure
time if we didn't

01:00:08.600 --> 01:00:10.484
have this sort of repeatable--

01:00:10.484 --> 01:00:12.400
DEAN BUONOMANO: You mean
man-made time, right?

01:00:12.400 --> 01:00:13.276
Clock time, you mean?

01:00:13.276 --> 01:00:15.025
AUDIENCE: Well I guess
what I'm asking is,

01:00:15.025 --> 01:00:17.270
like, is there something
fundamental about the idea

01:00:17.270 --> 01:00:18.890
of periodicity?

01:00:21.896 --> 01:00:24.020
How would we measure time
if there wasn't something

01:00:24.020 --> 01:00:26.475
that was symmetric that we
could always kind of start back

01:00:26.475 --> 01:00:26.840
at that point?

01:00:26.840 --> 01:00:27.570
DEAN BUONOMANO: So
no, I don't think so.

01:00:27.570 --> 01:00:29.360
I think it's just reproducibly.

01:00:29.360 --> 01:00:33.980
You can measure time
by an hour glass,

01:00:33.980 --> 01:00:36.540
it's something that's
doesn't have to be periodic.

01:00:36.540 --> 01:00:40.910
So I think man-made clocks
rely on this mechanism

01:00:40.910 --> 01:00:43.640
because it's an incredibly
useful symmetric one.

01:00:43.640 --> 01:00:45.605
And the best way to do
something continuously

01:00:45.605 --> 01:00:48.650
is with something
that's periodic.

01:00:48.650 --> 01:00:51.020
But you need some
sophisticated counter,

01:00:51.020 --> 01:00:52.950
and that was really
the main problem.

01:00:52.950 --> 01:00:54.860
But even if you
look at something

01:00:54.860 --> 01:00:59.870
like planetary motion, you
can tell the time of year

01:00:59.870 --> 01:01:01.970
by looking at the
positions of the planets.

01:01:01.970 --> 01:01:02.260
AUDIENCE: Well, right,
that's sort of my point.

01:01:02.260 --> 01:01:04.180
So even with an hourglass,
you could turn it over.

01:01:04.180 --> 01:01:04.400
There's like the resetting.

01:01:04.400 --> 01:01:06.358
DEAN BUONOMANO: You can,
but you don't have to.

01:01:06.358 --> 01:01:08.540
You can, but you
don't have to, right?

01:01:08.540 --> 01:01:10.640
You could have a
non-periodic hourglass.

01:01:10.640 --> 01:01:14.780
So I think periodicity is
something that, in our minds,

01:01:14.780 --> 01:01:17.120
because of the success
of man-made clocks,

01:01:17.120 --> 01:01:20.660
is something we naturally
think of as an ideal way

01:01:20.660 --> 01:01:21.450
to tell time.

01:01:21.450 --> 01:01:22.460
And it probably is.

01:01:22.460 --> 01:01:24.043
But interestingly,
and I think there's

01:01:24.043 --> 01:01:25.700
a downside to that,
which is people

01:01:25.700 --> 01:01:27.320
spent a bit too
much time looking

01:01:27.320 --> 01:01:29.900
for those oscillators
encounters in the brain.

01:01:29.900 --> 01:01:31.700
And I think that threw
the field off a bit

01:01:31.700 --> 01:01:34.260
because that's probably not
how the brain tells time.

01:01:34.260 --> 01:01:36.182
Yes, the brain has
oscillators, but it

01:01:36.182 --> 01:01:38.390
doesn't seem to have many
oscillator counter systems.

01:01:38.390 --> 01:01:42.530
So I think these metaphors
we use in the external world

01:01:42.530 --> 01:01:46.220
sometimes can put us back
a bit when we're overly

01:01:46.220 --> 01:01:47.067
influenced by them.

01:01:47.067 --> 01:01:47.900
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:01:47.900 --> 01:01:50.144
DEAN BUONOMANO: Thank you.

01:01:50.144 --> 01:01:51.560
CARL: Thanks
everybody for coming.

01:01:51.560 --> 01:01:52.277
And thanks, Dean.

01:01:52.277 --> 01:01:53.360
DEAN BUONOMANO: Thank you.

01:01:53.360 --> 01:01:56.410
[APPLAUSE]

